---
import Layout from '@/layouts/LoginLayout.astro';
import { getLang } from '@/lib/i18n/locale';
import { getChangelog } from '@/i18n/changelog';
const lang = getLang(Astro.request);
const t = getChangelog(lang);
---

<Layout
  title={t.pageTitle}
  description={t.description}
  lang={lang}
  noindex={true}
>
  <div class="page">

    <header class="page-header">
      <a href="/login" class="back-link">{t.backLink}</a>
    </header>

    <main class="content">
      <h1 class="page-title">{t.heading}</h1>
      <p class="page-sub">{t.sub}</p>

      <div class="entries">

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">July 10, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The website and dApp safety checker is faster and no longer leans on outside rate limits for its core data. The three largest phishing databases — MetaMask's blocklist (198,000+ domains), ScamSniffer's (345,000+), and Google Safe Browsing — now run from SusuFinance' own continuously-refreshed copy instead of being downloaded or queried on every check. Repeated checks of the same site return from a short-lived cache rather than calling the outside services again, and that cache is keyed by a one-way fingerprint of the address or URL — never the address or URL itself, so nothing you check is ever stored in readable form.</p>
            <p>Google Safe Browsing is now matched entirely against a local copy of its hash list, with a single confirmation call to Google only when there's a possible match — so it no longer counts against a daily quota. The checker verifies its own URL-matching against Google's official test cases on every refresh, and if Google ever changes those rules it disables the local match, falls back to the live lookup, and alerts the maintainer, so it can't quietly go wrong. The remaining live sources (GoPlus, URLScan, VirusTotal) are cached and capped so a burst of traffic can't exhaust their limits for everyone.</p>
            <p>Several privacy and abuse protections were hardened as well. The public checkers now identify a caller by their true network address, so a request can no longer spoof a header to slip past the per-minute rate limit. Internal diagnostic and analytics endpoints are now locked to the site owner. And everywhere the dashboard shows on-chain text — token names, transaction notes, wallet labels — that text is now escaped, so a maliciously-named token can't run code in your browser. None of these were known to have been exploited; they close the door before anyone tries.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">July 7, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>A Portfolio Assistant is now available on the Research and Bookkeeping pages. Click the <strong>✦ Ask AI</strong> button in the bottom-right corner to ask plain-English questions about your portfolio — your holdings, transaction history, cost basis, and unclassified items. The assistant answers from your data only; it has no access to any other account and does not give financial or tax advice. Free accounts get 5 questions per month, Starter 30, Pro 150, and Unlimited plans have no cap. Limits reset on the first of each month, and the badge on the button shows how many questions remain.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">July 6, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Exchanges and businesses can now publish their crypto receiving addresses as a verified list through SusuFinance Verify. The flow works in two steps: first, prove you control your domain by uploading a small JSON file at <code>/.well-known/almstins-verify.json</code> or adding a DNS TXT record — SusuFinance fetches it and confirms the challenge. Once your domain is proven, you configure a live endpoint on that same domain and an API key; SusuFinance polls the endpoint on a schedule and mirrors whatever addresses your system returns. Every address in that list is then published as "verified by yourdomain.com" on the public scanner at susufinance.com/verify/scan — no wallet connection, no signing, no manual entry required. The trust root is your domain, not a claim we take your word for.</p>
            <p>The three public safety endpoints — wallet address check, dApp / URL check, and verified address lookup — are now available as a documented JSON API for scripts and agents. Each endpoint accepts a <code>GET</code> request with a query parameter, returns machine-readable JSON, and includes full CORS headers so they can be called directly from a browser or agent context. Unauthenticated callers get 10 requests per minute per IP. To raise that to 60 per minute, generate an API key from the new API Keys section at the bottom of the Verify dashboard — the same page used by individuals proving wallet ownership and exchanges connecting their address list. Keys are labelled, revocable, and limited to five per account. The full endpoint reference is at <a href="/api-docs">susufinance.com/api-docs</a>.</p>
            <p>The wallet checker now tells you which chain an address belongs to — and warns you not to send the wrong asset to it. When you check an address, the result shows a chain badge (Ethereum / EVM, Bitcoin, Solana, Litecoin, Sui, or TRON) with a plain-English note beneath it. An EVM address warns you to confirm both sides are on the same network before sending, since the same 0x address is valid on Ethereum, Polygon, Avalanche, and others. A Bitcoin address tells you not to send ETH, SOL, or anything else to it. The warning is short and direct: sending the wrong asset to an address is permanent, and most losses happen before anyone checks.</p>
            <p>TRON addresses now get full safety checks: the GoPlus blacklist, Chainabuse community scam reports, wallet age, and TRC-20 token holdings are all available. The checker also recognises XRP, Dogecoin, Cardano, and Cosmos addresses and labels them clearly, so pasting one no longer returns a confusing "invalid address" — it tells you exactly which chain it belongs to. Full safety data for those four chains is coming; for now, the label and chain note are enough to prevent the most common mistake of sending funds across chains.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">July 5, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Your DeFi positions are more complete and easier to reach. SusuFinance now reads your Aave positions across all of Ethereum's markets — Core, Lido, EtherFi, and Horizon — not just the main one, so a position like staked-ETH supplied to the Lido market no longer goes missing from your DeFi tab. Each position now links straight through to its market on Aave, so you can open it in one click.</p>
            <p>Wallets are also steadier: if a wallet hits a temporary data hiccup while refreshing, it now keeps showing your last-known balances instead of turning into a blank error tin — a brief outage at a data provider no longer blanks a wallet that has good stored data.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">July 2, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Spam airdrops no longer clutter your books — and now you can see exactly what was set aside. Scam tokens and phishing airdrops (the ones with a website buried in their name) were always kept out of your holdings, gains, and tax totals, but silently. A new Filtered items view on the bookkeeping page lists everything that was filtered and <em>why</em>, so nothing is hidden — and if the filter ever catches something real, one click puts it back. You can also mark a genuine airdrop as income, or confirm a token as junk; your choice carries across your holdings, reconciliation, and tax. For your safety, token names are shown as plain text with links disabled, so the list can never be used against you.</p>
            <p>NFTs held in your connected wallets now have their own section, with a place to enter what each one cost — carried straight into the Year Summary PDF for your accountant. Crypto-card cashback and rebates (like Crypto.com's) now appear as a clearly-marked, non-taxable line under Income, so your preparer can confirm them instead of wondering where they went. And the Year Summary PDF now includes an appendix listing the filtered spam tokens, so the record is complete.</p>
            <p>The reconciliation panel got tidier: coins that already balance are hidden so the list shows only what needs attention, ordered by what matters most for tax, with a short plain-English explainer of what each status means.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 30, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Your bookkeeping now shows what your transactions actually cost you. A new Transaction Costs section on the bookkeeping page lists every exchange fee — date, source, asset, and dollar amount — with a running total for the year, plus the on-chain gas you paid summarized per network. Fees matter for tax: a fee paid to buy adds to your cost basis, and a fee paid to sell reduces your proceeds. They were always in your data; now they're itemized where you can see them, with an honest note on how many transactions actually carried a fee.</p>
            <p>Income is now valued at its fair market value at the exact moment you received it — the measure used for crypto income. When an exchange recorded the dollar value itself, that figure is used as-is; when it didn't, the value is filled from a historical price at the time of receipt rather than a daily average. Every income line now shows <em>where</em> its value came from — the exchange's own record, an estimate, or a stablecoin — so you and your accountant can see the basis behind every number. Anything that can't be priced is flagged for review instead of quietly counted as zero.</p>
            <p>The Year Summary PDF carries both through: income shows its value source per line, and a Transaction Costs summary sits alongside your gains. A toggle lets you include the full fee schedule — every line — or just the totals, depending on what your accountant prefers; the full schedule is the default.</p>
            <p>Also fixed: the "Fill Missing Prices" tool wasn't reliably saving the prices it looked up. It now works, and records the source and time behind every value it fills.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 25, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>A merchant can now prove they control a crypto receiving address — with no website and without connecting a wallet. On the Verify dashboard, register an address, then prove it by sending any tiny amount from that wallet, even to yourself. SusuFinance watches the public chain for it and marks the address Verified. Nothing is connected and nothing is signed for us; the only thing that proves you control an address is sending <em>from</em> it, and that's all this asks. An address can be claimed by one account only, so no one else can list yours as theirs.</p>
            <p>Every verified address gets a downloadable QR badge. Print it, or add it to your sign, invoice, or checkout, and a customer can scan it to confirm — on a public page, no account needed — that the address is really yours before they send anything.</p>
            <p>That check lives at <a href="/verify/scan">susufinance.com/verify/scan</a>: paste or scan any address and it answers two questions at once — whether it's a verified SusuFinance destination, and whether it's flagged by the scam, sanctions, and honeypot screens. It's the moment-before-you-pay check, built for the person doing the paying.</p>
            <p>Also fixed: if you'd tried the demo and later signed in, a leftover demo session could occasionally still show you the sample dashboard. Your signed-in account now always takes priority, and signing in clears any leftover demo session — so you'll never see sample data in place of your own.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 23, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The Year Summary export is now a verifiable record, not just a PDF. Alongside the summary you can download a small verification bundle that carries a cryptographic fingerprint of every line in the report, signed by SusuFinance. Together they turn an annual summary into something you can <em>prove</em> is genuine and unaltered — which matters the moment a number has to stand up to someone else: a tax filing, an audit, an inheritance, a dispute.</p>
            <p>Anyone you hand the bundle to can check it at <a href="/verify-record">susufinance.com/verify-record</a> — drop the file in and it confirms, right there in the browser, whether the record is authentic and whether a single figure has changed since it was generated. The check runs on your own device; nothing is uploaded. An accountant who would rather not take our word for anything can run the very same check offline. Importantly, this proves integrity and origin — that the record is a real SusuFinance export and hasn't been edited — it does not vouch for the tax math itself.</p>
            <p>Underneath, every row of the summary is hashed, those hashes are folded into a single fingerprint, and SusuFinance signs that fingerprint with a private key only it holds. The matching public key is published openly, so the signature can be checked by anyone and forged by no one — change one dollar in the report and the fingerprint no longer lines up. The exact figures behind your numbers are frozen at the moment you generate the export, so a summary you download today will still verify years from now, long after your live balances have moved on.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 14, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The wallet checker now has a prominent Scan QR button at the very top of the page. Checking an address with your phone's camera was already possible, but the entry point sat below the fold — and a phone is exactly the device most likely to have a camera ready. The button now sits above everything else, so it's the first thing you see. Tapping it switches to the wallet tab and opens the camera straight away; point it at a wallet QR code and the address is read on your device — nothing is sent until you run the check.</p>
            <p>The wallet checker's language control now offers all three languages at once — a single <strong>EN / ES / FR</strong> switcher in the top corner, with your current language highlighted. The French version of the checker went live a couple of days ago, but there was no way to reach it from the page itself; the toggle only flipped between English and Spanish. French is now one tap away from anywhere in the checker, alongside English and Spanish.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 13, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Search results in the Research ledger are now grouped and sortable. When a search returns transactions across multiple assets, results are organized into alphabetical symbol groups — all your ETH transactions together, then MATIC, then SOL, and so on — with a header between each group. A sort bar above the list lets you choose whether transactions within each group are ordered by date or by transaction amount, and toggle the direction up or down. Date ascending is the default, which reads as a chronological record of activity for each asset.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 12, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The Year Summary page now has a second level of detail. Clicking any wallet card opens a panel showing what changed inside that wallet during the year across three tabs: Holdings Delta, Net Change, and Transactions. Holdings Delta shows every token that moved — what you held at the start of the year, what you held at year end, and the difference. Net Change gives the same picture condensed to one line per symbol, useful for quick scanning. Transactions shows every on-chain send and receive for that wallet in the selected year with date, type, asset, and USD value. Tokens under a dollar in current value that weren't held at the start of the year are hidden from the delta so the list stays focused on what matters. Self-custody wallets now have their own section on the year summary page, separate from exchange accounts.</p>
            <p>The portfolio views — Holdings Delta, the portfolio table, and the reconciliation panel — no longer show phishing airdrop tokens. These are unsolicited tokens dropped into wallet addresses with scam URLs or instructions embedded in their symbol name: things like "VISIT TRUSTBOX.SITE TO CLAIM" or "CLAIM REWARDS ON T.LY/SHIBASWAP" or "*REDEEM WITHIN 7 DAYS." They appeared in holdings lists because wallet snapshots faithfully recorded everything found on-chain. They are now recognized by pattern — any token carrying a URL, a Telegram link, or a multi-word sentence as its symbol — and stripped from every view that displays token quantities. The filter runs at read time, so existing wallet snapshots are cleaned up immediately without a fresh sync.</p>
            <p>The Data Sync Status section has been reorganized. Wallets are now grouped by type — self-custody wallets and exchange-linked accounts in separate sections — making it easier to see at a glance which sources are syncing and when each last ran.</p>
            <p>A Privacy Policy is now available at <a href="/privacy">susufinance.com/privacy</a>, covering what data is collected, what is not, and why certain commitments are architectural rather than contractual.</p>
            <p>The wallet and website safety checker is now available in French at <a href="/wallet-checker/fr">susufinance.com/wallet-checker/fr</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 12, 2026 — TradfiTins</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The Budget Register and Debt tin entry lists now have sort controls. In the Budget Register, click the date or amount column header to sort; click again to reverse. Debt tin entries can be sorted by date, amount, or kind — payments separate from charges. Both default to date descending, which is the natural reading order for a running register.</p>
            <p>Descriptions in entry modals are now reliably editable. Clicking into an existing description field to make a change — a common action when a recurring bill amount or label shifts — previously required extra clicks or a workaround to trigger edit mode in certain cases. That is fixed.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 10, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Solana wallets now sync their full transaction history, not just current balances. Previously, adding a Solana wallet showed its balance but never imported the underlying transactions — so a transfer like moving tokens from an exchange to your Solana wallet had no on-chain record to match against, and stayed stuck as an unresolved item. Now syncing a Solana wallet pulls every on-chain token and SOL transfer into your ledger.</p>
            <p>Because those transfers now land in the same place as your exchange imports, the Resolve button can automatically pair an exchange withdrawal with its matching on-chain arrival and classify it as a non-taxable self-transfer — the same way it already works for Bitcoin and Ethereum wallets. Cost basis carries across the move instead of breaking at the chain boundary.</p>
            <p>A scheduled job now re-syncs Solana wallets every week, staggered alongside the existing Bitcoin, Ethereum, and Aave syncs, so your Solana history stays current without manual action. USD values for newly imported transactions are filled in by the existing price backfill.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 3, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>TradfiTins now has its own domain at <strong>tradifitins.com</strong>. Visiting the root redirects to the TradfiTins dashboard. When accessed from tradifitins.com, the navigation shows only TradfiTins links — Dashboard, Docs, and Upgrade — keeping the SusuFinance portfolio tools out of view for users who are here only for personal finance.</p>
            <p>The Shared Expenses section now has a dedicated URL anchor. Linking to <code>tradifitins.com/dashboard/petro-tins#splits</code> scrolls directly to the Shared Expenses section after the page loads, even though the data loads asynchronously.</p>
            <p>Each register entry in the Budget tin now has an optional payment URL field. Click any description or amount to enter edit mode, and a second input appears for the payment website. Save a URL once and a <code>🔗</code> link appears next to the bill name — click it to open the payment site directly. The URL carries over automatically when the bill rolls over to the next month.</p>
            <p>The splits tin layout has been redesigned around people rather than a bill grid. The top of each tin shows each person's name with a checkbox and their total balance — green with ✓ when fully paid, red with the amount remaining. A total line sits below. The add-bill form stays at the bottom. Clicking a person's name opens their responsibility panel, which now includes + Pay buttons per bill, inline bill editing, and a breakdown of how multi-line charges were calculated.</p>
            <p>Each bill assignment now stores a line-item breakdown — the individual formula and resolved value for every line. This is preserved permanently so that months later you can open the responsibility panel and see exactly what made up a charge: <code>=[Rent]*.25 = $350.00</code>, <code>=[Electric]*.5 = $186.59</code>, and so on.</p>
            <p>A new Shared Credit Card Expenses grid sits above the splits tins in the Shared Expenses section. Add bills that are paid on a credit card rather than out of the budget — choose the card, enter a description and amount, and the grid flags any charge that would push the card over its credit limit or past 90% utilization.</p>
            <p>Credit card tins now have a recurring charges register. Add charges like Netflix, Spotify, or a storage unit as recurring items. Check them off each month as they post to the card. Amounts and descriptions are editable inline. When all are checked, next month's list seeds automatically. One-time charges and payments remain in a collapsible section below.</p>
            <p>The FOUNDER promo code grants lifetime free access to TradfiTins with no payment required and no expiry date.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">June 2, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Budget register entries are now editable inline. Click any saved amount or description and it switches to an input field. Type the new value and press Enter or click away to save — Escape cancels. This makes it straightforward to update a recurring bill like an electric charge that changes month to month without deleting and re-entering the row.</p>
            <p>The splits bill form now supports multiple line items per person. Instead of one amount field, each person gets a stack of inputs with a small "+ add line" button below. Add <code>=[Rent]</code> on one line, <code>=[Electric]</code> on the next, and the form sums them automatically and shows the running total next to the person's name. Individual lines can be removed with ✕. The Add Bill button shows the derived total before you save.</p>
            <p>Splits formulas can now reference entries from your Budget Register by description. Type <code>=[Rent]</code> in a splits amount field and it pulls the current amount of the Rent entry from your linked budget tin. Budget entry chips appear below the amount fields as one-click shortcuts — click a chip and it fills the next empty line automatically. No need to remember exact description names.</p>
            <p>Clicking a person's name in the splits grid opens a responsibility panel showing every bill assigned to them, the amount owed for each, payment status, and a footer summary of total owed, paid, and remaining. Click the name again to close it. Names are now also clickable before any bills have been added, so the panel is accessible from the start.</p>
            <p>The Budget Register has a "+ Add row" button at the bottom of the blank entry section. Each click appends one more blank row for the current session — useful when a month has more entries than the default five rows.</p>
            <p>TradfiTins splits now support bill references in formulas. In any amount field — whether you're adding a shared bill or a personal one — you can type <code>=[Rent]</code> and it will substitute the current amount of the bill named Rent. From there you can do math on it: <code>=[Rent]*0.5</code> gives half the rent, <code>=[Rent]+[Utilities]</code> sums two bills together. The result previews in real time as you type so you can confirm the number before saving.</p>
            <p>Each person's column in the splits grid now has a small "+ and" button at the bottom. Clicking it opens a quick inline form — bill name and amount — that creates a bill assigned only to that person. Other people's cells for that bill stay blank rather than prompting you to set a value. This makes it straightforward to give each person their own list of bills without those bills cluttering everyone else's view.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">May 28, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Google Safe Browsing and VirusTotal are now active sources in the dApp and website checker, bringing the total to seven. Both were previously wired up but inactive due to missing API keys. Google Safe Browsing catches malware, phishing, and unwanted software across the broader web — not just crypto-specific threats. VirusTotal aggregates results from dozens of independent security engines and returns a count of how many flagged a given URL. A site that slips past the crypto-specific databases may still be caught here.</p>
            <p>The loading spinner on the dApp checker is now properly hidden between checks. A CSS specificity conflict — <code>display: flex</code> on the loading element overriding the browser's built-in <code>[hidden]</code> rule — meant the spinner was permanently visible on screen regardless of whether a check was running. All the state management was working correctly; it just had no visual effect. That's fixed.</p>
            <p>The yellow verdict label has been updated from "Proceed carefully" to "Cannot confirm this site is safe." The original wording implied permission to go ahead with a caveat. Yellow means there is not enough data to clear the site — not that it is probably fine.</p>
            <p>Two new FAQ entries have been added to the wallet checker, eligible to appear as Google rich results. The first explains why a known investment scam or fake trading platform may show yellow instead of red — phishing databases are built to catch wallet-draining sites, not deposit-based fraud — and how to report one. The second covers what to do if you have already been scammed: stop sending immediately, revoke any open token approvals at revoke.cash, report to the FBI's IC3 and the FTC, and contact your bank if traditional payment methods were involved.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">May 26, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>The wallet checker now works correctly for users who are not logged in. A routing oversight meant that the API backing the wallet address checker was only reachable by authenticated users or active sessions — anyone arriving at the page without an account would see a "Sign up free to unlock all features" message instead of results. That's fixed. The wallet checker has always been designed to require no account, and it now behaves that way for everyone.</p>
            <p>The dApp and website checker no longer times out on a cold start. Previously, the checker had to download three large security databases — MetaMask's phishing blocklist (198,000+ domains), ScamSniffer's database (345,000+ domains), and the OpenPhish feed — before it could return any results. On Render's free tier, where the service sleeps after inactivity, this caused the first check after a period of quiet to time out completely. The databases now load in the background the moment the service wakes up. If you check a URL before they finish loading, GoPlus and URLScan results return immediately and the remaining sources show "warming up — try again in a moment." A second check seconds later returns the full picture from all seven sources.</p>
            <p>The two action cards at the top of the wallet checker page have been relabeled. "Malicious site connection" is now "Paste your URL here" and "Investing in a known scam" is now "Paste a wallet address" — making it immediately clear what each card does without having to read the input placeholder first.</p>
            <p>Added FAQPage structured data (JSON-LD) to the wallet checker page. The twelve FAQ entries — covering honeypot scams, wallet drainers, Tornado Cash, what red and yellow verdicts mean, and what to do when a check returns a flag — are now marked up in a format Google can surface as rich results directly in search. This makes the answers findable for people searching those questions before they have a problem, not just after.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">May 24, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Added a second sign-up prompt at the bottom of the demo vault page. The existing "Sign up free" button lives at the top of the page, but someone who scrolls through the full demo — all three wallets, exchanges, and on-chain data — ends up at the footer with no obvious next step. That's the moment of highest intent and it was being wasted. The new prompt reads "Ready to track your own portfolio? Sign up free — no credit card required. Your vault, your data." It sits just above the footer FAQ section, where the demo naturally ends.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">May 23, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>When a wallet tin fails to load its balance data — a network timeout, an API outage, or a bad response from the data provider — the tin now shows exactly what happened instead of going blank or silently displaying zero. You get a short message explaining the connection failed, a ref code (a short ID like <code>FA5B-1K2M9</code>) you can copy and send to support, and a Try again button that re-fetches without reloading the page. Behind the scenes, an alert fires automatically so the issue is already being looked into before you think to report it. The ref code is click-to-select for easy copying.</p>
            <p>When a logged-in user triggers demo mode — for example to show the app to a friend — they are now logged out first before the demo starts. This keeps your real portfolio private when handing the screen to someone else. After the demo, just sign back in to return to your account.</p>
            <p>Bitcoin wallets now sync automatically every week. Previously, your BTC balance and transaction history would only update when you manually triggered a sync from the vault. Now a scheduled job runs every Monday in the early hours, fetches the latest transactions from Blockstream, and updates your balance snapshot — so your cold storage tin stays current without any action on your part.</p>
            <p>The same automatic weekly sync was also added for EVM wallet transactions (Ethereum, Polygon, Avalanche) and Aave DeFi positions. All three run on a staggered schedule so they don't overlap. If you haven't opened the app in a week, your numbers will still reflect what happened on-chain.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="entry">
          <time class="entry-date">May 21, 2026</time>
          <div class="entry-body">
            <p>Each tin on the vault dashboard now has a small corner flag that tells you what you're looking at at a glance. Wallet tins get a chain-colored triangle — gold for Bitcoin, silver for Ethereum, violet for Solana, and so on — with a chain-link icon. Exchange tins (Coinbase, Kraken, Gemini, etc.) get a muted fold with a bank icon instead. The colors match each chain's established identity, so once you learn them you don't have to read the label.</p>
            <p>The "What's new" link on the home page has moved to the right side of the screen, below the portfolio preview, where it has room to breathe.</p>
            <p>The wallet checker is now available in Spanish at <a href="/wallet-checker/es">/wallet-checker/es</a> — fully translated including all threat explanations, modals, verdict labels, FAQ, and safety tips. Crypto terms like wallet, token, phishing, and honeypot are kept in English, which is how the Spanish-speaking crypto community actually uses them.</p>
